Coxsackie B4 & diabetes 980602214150
[1
Date: Tue, 2 Jun 1998 22:25:53 -0600
From: Hal Nash <hnash@wyoming.com>

This sounds more like a case of cross-reactivity than autoimmunity. Or am
I splitting hairs here? The normal immune response to one of the 11
proteins of the Coxsackie B4 virus just happens to cross-react with a
protein found in pancreatic islets. This seems to me to be more accurately
described as accidental. It is my understanding that autoimmunity results
from the "escape" of sequestered clones which recognize human antigens.
Regardless, the discovery is significant and lends support to an old
hypothesis that all disease, including organic disease, is the result of a
microbe. The recent ProMED-mail discussion regarding _Chlamydia
pneumoniae_ and its possible link to atherosclerosis is but another example.
--
Hal B. Nash
Asst. Professor of Biology
Western Wyoming College
Rock Springs, WY 82901
e-mail: hnash@wyoming.com
