[3
Date: Thu, 04 Jun 1998 02:19:27 -0400
From: Alexander, Charles M. <charles_alexander@merck.com>

The newspaper article by Jonathan Leake and Mark Macaskill regarding
diabetes contains several factual errors and reaches a conclusion that
cannot be supported by the bulk of scientific evidence.
Type 1 diabetes is a serious condition affecting children. The tragedy of
type 1 diabetes must be acknowledged. However, for perspective, an
analysis of the U.S. NHANES database gives an estimate for a U.S.
population representing 170.5 million (M) civilian, non-institutionalized
American adults and would suggest that 7.9 million have diabetes by
history, an additional 4.7 million have a fasting glucose > 126 mg/dl, but
are unaware that they have diabetes, and 11.6 million have impaired fasting
glucose (fasting glucose 110-125 mg/dl). Of the adults with diabetes by
history, approximately 90% appear to have type 2 diabetes. The bulk of the
other 2 groups almost certainly do not have type 1 diabetes.
Therefore, only a very small number of patients with diabetes have type 1.
A virus has never been seriously considered to be a possible cause of type
2 diabetes. Viral etiologies have been suggested for type 1 diabetes
(present in less than 10% of adults with diabetes), but genetic etiologies
are also possible. Alternatively, type 1 diabetes may require both genetic
susceptibility and viral exposure. It is not clear that the viral exposure
must be a single virus. It is possible that a susceptible individual if
exposed to one of multiple viral species may later develop type 1 diabetes.
The bulk of the increased prevalence of diabetes globally appears to be
from type 2 diabetes associated with increasing obesity, sedentary
lifestyle, television, etc.
The characterization of diabetes as a growing epidemic caused by a virus
spreading across the UK or anywhere else on the globe cannot be supported
by the available facts. There are enough growing viral epidemics spreading
across the globe (e.g. HIV). We don't need to add diabetes to the list.
--
Charles M. Alexander, M.D.
Outcomes Research & Management
Merck & Co., Inc.
P.O. Box 4 WP39-170
West Point, PA 19486
